<subSubSection pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1436,476,791]" box="[151,572,476,503]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,530,476,503]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Number of specimens recorded.</emphasis>
20.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1436,476,791]" box="[199,1072,512,539]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,512,539]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Distribution.</emphasis>
Europe. 
<collectingCountry box="[454,553,513,539]" name="Portugal" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Portugal</collectingCountry>
: one province (Trás-os-Montes e Alto Douro).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1436,476,791]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,300,549,575]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Ecology.</emphasis>
The only site where 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dolichopodinae" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1767" box="[546,696,549,575]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Poecilobothrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nobilitatus">
<emphasis box="[546,696,549,575]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">P. nobilitatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been encountered in 
<collectingCountry box="[991,1086,549,575]" name="Portugal" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Portugal</collectingCountry>
was a permanent pasture (Lameiro) crossed by a small stream, with 
<taxonomicName box="[583,714,585,611]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Populus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[583,675,585,611]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Populus</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[725,819,585,611]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Salix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[725,781,585,611]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Salix</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[871,979,585,611]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[871,941,585,611]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Rubus</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
among others on its banks and a 
<taxonomicName authorityName="F. M. Vázquez" authorityYear="1998" baseAuthorityName="C. Vicioso" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pyrenaica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Quercus pyrenaica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
dominated forest higher up the slopes. In northwestern Europe, this is a very eurytopic species that can be found in huge numbers on and near shallow water bodies in both wooded and open biotopes, where the males display conspicuous courtship behaviour (
<bibRefCitation author="Lunau, K." box="[622,763,693,719]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="465 - 479" refId="ref32719" refString="Lunau, K. (1992) Mating behaviour in the long-legged fly Poecilobothrus nobilitatus L. (Diptera, Dolichopodidae): courtship behaviour, male signalling and mating success. Zoologische Beitrage, Neue Folge, 34 (3), 465 - 479." type="journal article" year="1992">Lunau 1992</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1436,476,791]" box="[199,743,728,755]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,728,755]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Rarity (%).</emphasis>
1.1 (very rare). Very common (FL).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1436,476,791]" box="[199,612,764,791]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,386,764,791]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Activity period.</emphasis>
August–September.
</paragraph>
